ABSTRACT
To date, the implications of prostaglandin I2 (PGI
2
), a prominent lipid mediator for modulation of immune
responses, has not been clearly understood in Brucella infection. In this study, we found that cyclooxygenase-2
(COX-2) was signicantly expressed in both infected bone marrow-derived macrophages (BMMs) and RAW
264.7 cells. Prostaglandin I2 synthase (PTGIS) expression was not signicantly changed, and PGI
2
receptor (PTGIR)
expression was downregulated in BMMs but upregulated in RAW 264.7 macrophages at late infection. Here, we
presented that PGI
2
, a COX-derived metabolite, was produced by macrophages during Brucella infection and its
production was regulated by COX-2 and IL-10. We suggested that PGI
2
and selexipag, a potent PGI
2
analogue,
inhibited Brucella internalization through IP signaling which led to down-regulation of F-actin polymerization
and p38
α
MAPK activity. Administration with selexipag suppressed immune responses and resulted in a notable
reduction in bacterial burden in spleen of Brucella-challenged mice. Taken together, our study is the rst to
characterize PGI
2
synthesis and its effect in evasion strategy of macrophages against Brucella infection.
1. Introduction
Brucella are non-motile intracellular bacteria, acquired advantage
traits to invade and proliferate within both professional and non-
professional phagocytes leading to chronic infection. Taken up by
macrophages, the deceptive B. abortus inhibits a number of bactericidal
processes such as phagosome-lysosome fusion and oxidative burst using
its prominent virulence factors (i.e. lipopolysaccharide, type-IV secre-
tion system and BvrR/BvrS system) (Byndloss and Tsolis, 2016). Once
microbial pathogens internalized into host macrophages, a vast number
of functional biomolecules are induced from host to control the patho-
gens which in return also trigger host cells to produce molecules such as
lipids and proteins to favor their survival in hostile environment. After
Brucella infection, it was reported that human macrophage-like cells
experienced a metabolic shift including modulation of a key metabolic
pathway – tricarboxylic acid cycle, and mitochondrial localization (Czyz
et al., 2017).
For intracellular bacteria, their encounter with macrophages is often
considered as fatal but also opportunistic to successfully overcome im-
mune system of the host. Phagocytosis is an essential process in innate
immunity to degrade microbial pathogens and to initiate immune re-
sponses by presenting pathogen-associated molecular patterns to other
responsible immune cells. How Brucella interfere with phagocytosis is
not fully understood. Different cells produce different eicosanoid prod-
ucts. In macrophages, toll-like receptor activation triggers the produc-
tion of a number of prostaglandins (PGs) – catalyzed products of
arachidonic acid (AA), but which type of PGs and their quantities
induced are strongly dependent on activation status (Norris et al., 2011).
Besides, expression of the receptors for their respective eicosanoids is
also cell and tissue specic. In cyclooxygenase (COX) pathway, the
conversion of AA to PGs is dependent on COX enzymes. In bacterial
infection conditions, the rising levels of COX-2 are crucial to mount
inammatory responses. The relevance of using indomethacin (a COX
inhibitor) to clear B. abortus infection which was thought to via

inhibition of PGs has been suggested, however how COXs impact both
innate and adaptive immunity against B. abortus infection requires
further investigation (Stevens et al., 1992).
Prostaglandin I2 (PGI
2
), also known as prostacyclin, is an immuno-
suppressive lipid regulator produced by two step conversion of AA. By
acting through PGI
2
receptor (PTIGR – IP), PGI
2
triggers up-regulation of
cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) and down-regulation of NF-κB
resulting in modulation of physiological and immunological responses.
Physiological roles and immunomodulatory functions of AA-derived PGs
have been relatively well established (Hata and Breyer, 2004; Ricciotti
and FitzGerald, 2011). While the role of PGI
2
in inammation is
controversial, its well-known function is anti-inammatory due to its
powerful effect on cardiovascular homeostasis (Majed and Khalil, 2012).
However, its role as immunomodulatory agent is also considerable,
especially on development of CD4
+
T cell subsets and modulation of
group 2 innate lymphoid cell responses (Boswell et al., 2011; Zhou et al.,
2016).
Up to now, no studies have investigated functional characterization
of PGI
2
against Brucella infection. In this study, we investigated how host
macrophages produced PGI
2
in its favor to counter bacterial infection,
and the underappreciated role of PGI
2
in suppressing internalization of
B. abortus through IP signaling in macrophages – sentinels of the innate
immunity was also addressed.
2. Materials and methods
2.1. Reagents
All primary antibodies were purchased from Cell Signaling Tech-
nology (MA, USA), while HRP-conjugated goat anti-rabbit IgG antibody
was obtained from Abcam (Cambridge, UK). The 6-keto-PGF1
α
ELISA
kit (ADI-901-004) was purchased from Enzo Life Science (NY, USA). All
COX-1, COX-2 inhibitor and selexipag used in this study were purchased
from Cayman Chemicals (MI, USA) except PGI
2
(Sigma-Aldrich, MO,
USA), and reconstituted in DMSO to obtain stock solutions. NS-398 is a
specic potent COX-2 inhibitor, NS-304 is one of prominent PGI
2
ana-
logues. There are several reasons why NS-304 (selexipag) was chosen
instead of PGI
2
or other analogues to our experiments. First, because
PGI
2
(epoprostenol) is unstable in vivo, and also, some of PGI
2
analogues
have been shown to stimulate other prostanoid receptors or FcR receptor
which may independently regulate phagocytic signaling while NS-304
exclusively acts on IP (Dorris and Peebles, 2012). Working solutions
were freshly prepared prior to performing experiments.
2.2. Bacterial strain and culture conditions
The smooth, virulent B. abortus 544 biovar 1 strain (ATCC 23448)
was kindly provided by the Laboratory of Bacteriology Division in An-
imal and Plant Quarantine Agency in Korea and grown in Brucella broth
(BD Biosciences, CA, USA) at 37 ◦C until stationary phase.
2.3. Cells and culture conditions
Murine macrophage RAW 264.7 cells were purchased from American
Type Culture Collection (VA, USA). The cells were maintained in RPMI
1640 (Gibco, CA, USA) supplemented with 10% heat-inactivated fetal
bovine serum (FBS) (Gibco, CA, USA), and with or without 100 U/ml
penicillin and 100
μ
g/ml streptomycin (Gibco, CA, USA) at 37 ◦C in 5%
CO
2
atmosphere. Bone marrow-derived macrophages (BMMs) were
isolated and cultured using L-cell conditioned medium as previously
described with modications (Weischenfeldt and Porse, 2008). Briey,
BMMs were aseptically collected from femur and tibia, then maintained
in RPMI containing FBS and a mixture of penicillin and streptomycin in
culture plates (35 ×10 mm Nunclon™ Delta Surface) (ThermoFisher,
MA, USA). After 3 days, 10 ml of fresh medium without antibiotics was
added to the plates. At day 7, cells were washed with PBS to remove
non-binding cells, then the cells were collected to perform the suc-
ceeding experiments.
2.4. Bacterial internalization and intracellular replication assay
These assays were performed as described elsewhere with modi-
cations (Reyes et al., 2017). Briey, 5 ×10
4
RAW 264.7 macrophages
were seeded to reach the conuent of 80% in 96-well culture plate (SPL,
Life Sciences, Gyeonggi, Korea) after 24 h of incubation, subsequently
RPMI 1640 was used to replace the culture medium. The cells then were
infected with multiplicity of infection (MOI) of 100 (150×g in 10 min,
18 ◦C). At 0, 15 and 30 min post-infection (p.i.), infected cells were
washed once with PBS to remove unbound bacteria and then incubated
with RPMI supplemented with 10% FBS and 60
μ
g/ml gentamicin
(Sigma-Aldrich, MO, USA) for 1 h to kill remaining extracellular
bacteria.
To determine Brucella intracellular replication, infected cells were
incubated at 37 ◦C in 5% CO
2
atmosphere for 1 h, washed one time with
PBS. The media were changed to RPMI containing 10% FBS supple-
mented with 60
μ
g/ml gentamicin. At 6, 24, and 48 h p. i., cells were
washed two times prior to lysis by distilled water and plated on Brucella
agar plates (SPL, Life Sciences, Gyeonggi, Korea).
2.5. Depletion of endogenous IP and IL-10
A concentration of 2.5 ×10
5
RAW 264.7 macrophages were seeded
to reach about 50% conuence in 6-well plate cultured for 24 h. To
knockdown endogenous IP and IL-10, PTGIR siRNA duplexes (assay ID:
MSS247589, ThermoFisher, MA, USA) and IL-10 siRNA (sc-39635,
Santa Cruz, CA, USA), respectively, were prepared with Lipofectamine
RNAiMAX (ThermoFisher, MA, USA) prior to transfection for 30 h.
Control siRNA-A (sc-37007, Santa Cruz, CA, USA) was used as a negative
siRNA. Knockdown efciency is considered signicant when a target
siRNA decreased expression of a gene of interest to at least 80% as
compared to negative siRNA. All siRNA interfering experiment was
conducted in duplicate samples in three independent experiments.
2.6. RNA extraction and quantitative RT-PCR
Using RNeasy kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany), the total RNA was
extracted from cells at multiple time points. Briey, 500
μ
l of RiboEx
(GeneAll, SU, Korea) and 230
μ
l of chloroform (Sigma-Aldrich, MO,
USA) were added into one well, the cells were vortexed vigorously for 1
min, incubated at 37 ◦C in a heating block for 5 min then repeated one
time before being subjected to high speed centrifugation (12,000 rpm)
for 15 min at 4 ◦C.
qRT-PCR was performed as described elsewhere (Flores et al., 2019).
Briey, a 20
μ
l mixture including 10
μ
l of GoTag® qPCR Master Mix
(Promega, WI, USA), 9
μ
l of functional primers (10 pM, Tables 1) and 1
μ
l cDNA was denatured at 95 ◦C for 10 min and the reaction was
repeated for 39 cycles at 95 ◦C for 15 s followed by 60 ◦C for 1 min. The
transcriptional proles were normalized to the housekeeping gene
β-actin, and the relative gene expression was quantitated using 2
−ΔΔCT
method (Livak and Schmittgen, 2001).

2.7. Immunoblot analysis
Pre-treated with either vehicle or PGI
2
(10
μ
g/ml), RAW 264.7 cells
were infected with B. abortus for 30 min. The cells were washed three
times with PBS, then lysed with Radioimmunoprecipitation assay buffer
containing 2% Protease Inhibitor Cocktail (Promega, WI, USA). The cell
lysates were boiled for 5 min in 2x sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) buffer
(ratio 1:1; Bio-Rad, CA, USA), and subjected to electrophoresis using
10% SDS gels (ThermoFisher, MA, USA). The separated proteins were
transferred onto nitrocellulose membrane (Millipore, MA, USA) for 20
min using a semi-dry blotting system (ATTO, Tokyo, Japan). After
transferring, the nitrocellulose membranes were blocked with blocking
buffer (Tris-buffered saline, 0.1% Tween 20; TBS-T containing 5%
bovine serum albumin (GenDEPOT, Barker, TX, USA)) for 1 h at room
temperature, then incubated overnight at 4 ◦C with specic primary
antibodies in blocking buffer. The membranes were washed ve times
(10 min each) using TBS-T, then incubated with horseradish peroxidase
(HRP)-conjugated goat anti-mouse IgG antibody (Abcam, Cambridge,
UK) with blocking buffer for 1 h at room temperature. The membranes
were washed three times with TBS-T prior to signal detection using
ChemiDoc XRS +system (Bio-Rad, CA, USA) with luminol solution
(EzWestLumi plus, ATTO, Tokyo, Japan). ImageJ (NIH) was used to
quantify signal intensity.
2.8. In vivo experiment
All animal studies were performed with permission from the Animal
Ethical Committee of Chonbuk National University (Authorization
Number CBNU-2018-101). Specic pathogen-free ICR female mice (7
weeks old; Samtako, Osan, Korea) were randomly distributed into four
groups of 8 mice each and acclimatized for 10 days prior to giving
treatments. Both Brucella-infected and Brucella-uninfected groups were
orally pretreated with 0.1 ml selexipag (10
μ
g/ml in PBS) or 0.1 ml
vehicle (1% DMSO in PBS) in three consecutive days prior to infection
and continued until 14 days p. i. (d.p.i.) using sterilized gavage needles.
All groups of used mice were monitored carefully to assure no abnormal
clinical symptoms appeared. Bacterial challenge was performed intra-
peritoneally with a dose of 2 ×10
4
colony-forming units (CFUs) of
B. abortus. Blood was collected on day 3 and day 14 p. i. Through the tail
vein. After 2 weeks p. i., mice were sacriced; spleens and livers were
carefully removed and weighed. In Brucella-challenged mice, an amount
of 0.05 g of spleen was homogenized in PBS and plated onto agar plates
by serial dilution. The plates were incubated for 72 h at 37 ◦C to
determine CFU number. Spleen was used for estimating the number of
CFUs due to several reasons. First, spleen is among the most prominently
infected organs beside liver during Brucella infection. And second, the
higher number of bacterial colonization in spleen than other organs is
found after 14 d. p.i.. (Grillo et al., 2012).

for 6 h prior to infection. At 30 min p. i., cells were xed with

μ
g/ml
lysophosphatidylcholine containing 1
μ
M tetramethyl rhodamine
isothiocyanate-phalloidin was applied to permeabilize and stain the
cells for 30 min at room temperature. Subsequently, the cells were
gently collected using cell scraper and centrifuged at 300×g for 5 min at

2.10. Bactericidal assay
After the bacteria were grown for 2 days to reach stationary phase,
10
μ
l from 1 ×10
6
CFU/ml were added to various concentrations of
selexipag to have the total of 100
μ

incubated for 4, 8, 24, and 48 h. CFUs were determined by serial di-

2.11. Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA)
ELISA was performed as manufacturer’s instructions to measure 6-
keto-PGF1
α
at the absorbance of 405 nm. Briey, 100
μ
l of macrophage
culture media, 50
μ
l of blue conjugate and 50
μ
l of yellow antibody were
added into the provided wells followed by incubating at room temper-
ature on a plate shaker for 2 h. Then the wells were washed several times
before adding the appropriate substrate solution to initiate the enzyme
reaction. Quantitation of 6-keto-PGF1
α
was calculated based on build-
ing curve tting of the standards.
2.12. Statistical analysis
GraphPad Instat 3 (GraphPad Software Inc.) was employed to sta-
tistically evaluate the data using two-tailed Student’s t-test or one-way
ANOVA. Figures were drawn using GraphPad Prism software 5
(GraphPad Software Inc.). Results with P <0.05 were considered sta-
tistically signicant.
2.13. Cytotoxicity assay
RAW 264.7 macrophages were cultured in a 96-well plate for 24 h to
reach the conuency of 80%. After that, a wide range of concentration of
PGI
2
(1, 10, 100
μ
g/ml), selexipag (1, 10, 100
μ
g/ml), NS-398 (1, 10,
100, 500
μ
g/ml) was added to the well and incubated for 48 h. Cell
viability was measured using a colorimetric 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-
yl)-2,5-diphenyltetrazolium bromide (MTT) (Sigma-Aldrich, MO, USA)
assay, the plates were read at 540 nm by a spectrophotometer.

found that COX-2 expression is signicantly up-regulated over examined

uninfected cells (Fig. 1C and D) while its isoform COX-1 is constitutively

3.2. PGI
2
is induced during B. abortus infection and its production is
controlled by COX-2 and IL-10
We hypothesized that COX-2, and not COX-1, catalyzes AA to PG
products; to support our hypothesis, the cytotoxicity of a specic COX-2
inhibitor (NS-398) was checked (Fig. 2A), a range of concentration of
NS-398 was applied to B. abortus-infected RAW 264.7 cells to quantitate
the production of PGI
2
via its stable hydrolyzed product 6-keto-PGF1
α
.
PGI
2
production was then examined by BMMs and RAW 264.7 macro-
phages upon B. abortus infection at 6 and 48 h p. i. PGI
2
production in
Brucella-infected BMM culture supernatants was negatively regulated by
NS-398 (Fig. 2B) in which a concentration of 10
μ
g/ml signicantly
decreased the PG secretion at both examined time points (P <0.05) as
compared to infected cells while PGI
2
level in culture supernatants was
detected at a very low level in uninfected cells. We then continued
investigating whether RAW 264.7 macrophages secrete PGI
2
into cell
supernatant; similarly, Fig. 2C showed that incubating the cells with NS-
398 after infection dampened PGI
2
production in Brucella-infected RAW
264.7 cells in a dose-dependent manner at 6 and 48 h p. i. (P <0.05).
Moreover, a non-cytotoxic concentration of 10
μ
g/ml of FR122047 (a
specic COX-1 inhibitor) was deployed to evaluate the effect of COX-1
on PGI
2
synthesis in RAW 264.7 macrophages. Consistent with our
ndings on transcription level of COX-1 during B. abortus infection,
there was no signicant difference in 6-keto-PGF1
α
level in FR122047-
treated cell cultured supernatants as compared to that of mocked
treatment (data not shown). PGI
2
secretion in uninfected RAW 264.7
supernatants was also detected with a modest amount. It is important to
note that the reduction in PGI
2
secretion in NS-398 treated cell super-
natants could be mainly due to inhibitory effect of NS-398 and partly
due to decreasing cell viability.
In order to understand the mechanism behind PGI
2
induction, we
rst checked the knockdown efciency of IL-10 siRNA by qRT-PCR (data
not shown) then transfected IL-10 siRNA to RAW 264.7 cells prior to
infection to see whether temporarily blocking IL-10 affects COX-2 and
PTGIS expression, and PGI
2
production. As indicated in Fig. 2D, abro-
gation of endogenous IL-10 signicantly led to a signicant increase in
PGI
2
level in macrophage cultured supernatants at late infection as
compared to negative siRNA-transfected group (P <0.05).

PGI
2
on Brucella internalization was observed even at the concentration
as low as 0.1
μ
g/ml (data not shown). In intracellular growth, however,
post-treatment with PGI
2
showed no statistical difference in CFU num-
ber compared to vehicle at all examined time points. To consolidate the
CFUs observation, the highest non-cytotoxicity concentration of selex-
ipag – a potent PGI
2
analogue (Fig. 3C), was deployed and showed the
similar outcome in RAW 264.7 macrophages against B. abortus infection
(Fig. 3D). We also investigated the potential inhibitory effect of PGI
2
and
NS-304 on another infamous intracellular bacteria – Salmonella enterica
Typhymurium; however, it appeared that both treatments (with a
number of tested concentrations) did not result in signicant changes in
number of internalized Salmonella (data not shown). These ndings
indicated the potential role of PGI
2
signaling in Brucella uptake, we thus
further investigated relevant aspects contributed to phagocytic signaling
in Brucella infection.
3.4. PGI
2
mediates IP to inhibit B. abortus internalization via MAPK
pathway and decrease F-actin polymerization
To observe the interaction of PGI
2
-IP signaling in macrophage
infection model, transient transfection assay was employed in which
knockdown efciency of IP was checked by qRT-PCR (data not shown).
We determined that when endogenous IP was depleted, the inhibitory
effect of PGI
2
was neutralized resulting in signicant recovery of CFUs in
PTGIR-decient macrophage pretreated with PGI
2
(Fig. 4A). Since
mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs) phosphorylation is a com-
mon post-translational modication induced in macrophages against
microbial infection to amplify intracellular signals, and adding exoge-
nous PGI
2
and its analogue suppressed bacterial invasion in macro-
phages, we then examined the relevance of MAPKs pathway in this
study. The results suggested that phosphorylation level of p38
α
was
markedly down-regulated (≤2 fold) while that of ERK1/2 showed
modest reduction (Fig. 4B). We then tested the hypothesis whether PGI
2
is involved in cytoskeleton rearrangement in macrophages. In harmony
with the down-regulation of MAPKs activity, F-actin content quantita-
tion showed a signicant decrease in uorescence intensity in PGI
2
-
pretreated cells compared to mocked treatment macrophages (Fig. 4C).
Our results indicated that IP activation was required to initiate PGI
2
-
mediated bacterial phagocytosis, and effect of PGI
2
was associated with
controlling bacterial uptake into macrophages likely through MAPKs
cascade which subsequently decreased F-actin polymerization.
3.5. Selexipag administration suppresses immune responses and reduces
bacterial load in a mouse model
After collecting potential interesting in vitro results, we questioned
the relevance of using PGI
2
analogue as a novel therapeutic, and
immunomodulatory effect of the analogue in Brucella systemic infection
in a mouse model. We then started examining the direct bacterial killing
capacity of selexipag, a potent PGI
2
analogue, using various concen-
trations (Fig. 5A). The survivability of B. abortus decreased in a dose-
dependent manner suggesting selexipag has a slight bactericidal effect
against the intracellular bacteria. All orally treatment groups were
checked closely, and no abnormal symptoms were noted. In uninfected
groups, the total weight of the spleens and livers in either NS-304 treated

Next, since PGI
2
is a potent immunosuppressive metabolite, and
cytokine level of serum indicates cytokine secretion from splenic cells,
we quantitated serum collected from both Brucella-infected and non-
infected animals to investigate the effect of selexipag on cytokine pro-
duction. As shown in Fig. 5D, in the Brucella-challenged groups, a small
amount of 4 among 6 examined cytokines was observed at 3 d. p.i.
including TNF-
α
, IFN-γ, MCP-1 and IL-6 as compared to control whereas
IL-10 and IL-12p70 were not detectable. At 14 d. p.i., however, levels of
TNF-

, IFN-γ, MCP-1, and IL-6 drastically declined (P <0.05) in
selexipag-treated group as compared to control while the two cytokines
IL-10 and IL-12p70 were again not detected. Taken together, these re-
sults indicated the anti-inammatory effect of selexipag upon B. abortus
infection in vivo.
4. Discussion
Understanding host-pathogen interaction is essential to disease pre-
vention and generation of proper treatments. During pathogen invasion
into host cells, activated macrophages produce numerous molecules to
ght off the threat from pathogens, and microbial pathogens also
secreted other molecules to exploit host cells for their survival in return
(Ribet and Cossart, 2015). B. abortus, an intracellular microbial path-
ogen, is one of the causes of brucellosis resulting in a signicant eco-
nomic burden in many developing countries. Professional phagocytes
are capable of phagocytosis and processing extrinsic microorganisms to
initiate immune responses in both innate and acquired immune systems
to control potential infection. Brucella, however, is able to escape
phagolysosome fusion to successfully proliferate inside the sentinel cells
leading to chronic infection (Celli, 2019). In response to bacterial
infection, lipid mediators tightly interlinked with their protein coun-
terparts - cytokines are among highly induced molecules by macro-
phages required to regulate host defense system (Mukhopadhyay et al.,
2019; Ricciotti and FitzGerald, 2011).
PGI
2
is a lipid mediator in eicosanoid family metabolized by
sequential actions of phospholipase A2, COX and PGI synthase (Dennis
and Norris, 2015). The prostaglandin is generally known as the mediator
of G-protein-coupled IP, and activation of IP leads to production of
effector molecules which subsequently phosphorylate other key proteins
to release inhibitory effects (Dorris and Peebles, 2012). Prostacyclin
synthesis is dependent on cell types and stimuli; for example, PGI
2
is
constitutively induced in epithelial cells and smooth muscle cells (Wu
and Liou, 2005). On the other hand, inammatory conditions trigger
vascular cells and macrophages to produce PGI
2
(Brock et al., 1999; Wen
et al., 1997). The role of COX-1 and COX-2 in PGI
2
synthesis in car-
diovascular system is controversial (Kirkby et al., 2012; Ricciotti et al.,
2013). Previously, the involvement of COX pathway against Brucella
infection in human macrophages was suggested, in which several PG-
and leukotriene-related genes were expressed (Gagnaire et al., 2016).
But it is not clear whether PGI
2
is induced and its role in microbial
infection needs to be claried. After transcriptional proling of genes
potentially involved in PGI
2
synthesis, we found that PTGIS mRNA level
in both BMMs and RAW 264.7 cells was not signicantly affected by
B. abortus infection suggesting PGI
2
secretion may not necessarily
depend on transcription level of PTGIS in Brucella-stimulated RAW
264.7 cells. Additionally, COX-2 was found to be signicantly expressed
while COX-1 expression was constitutive indicating elevated COX-2 is
likely important to activate and mediate other subsequent inammatory
signaling pathways in the context of Brucella-macrophage interaction.
On the other hand, the contrast PTGIR mRNA level between BMMs and
RAW 264.7 macrophages could be attributed to dissimilarities in their

8
physiological functions which have been not extensively documented as
a huge number of proteins related to phagosomes between the two cell
types were reported (Guo et al., 2015). It is possible that the difference
(s) may go beyond phagosomes. Comprehensive evaluation at tran-
scriptional, proteomic and metabolomic levels in all signaling cascades
would provide insights into these potential distinctions.
Investigation on the ability of Brucella-stimulated macrophages to
induce PGI
2
production also provided insights on biosynthesis of the
prostaglandin as PGI
2
was signicantly secreted from infected BMMs
and RAW 264.7 macrophages, and the PGI
2
production increased over
time as compared to uninfected cells. Because AA conversion to PGs is
tightly COX-dependent, we harnessed similar results when the specic
COX-2 inhibitor (NS-398) was used to attenuate PGI
2
production while
treating RAW 264.7 cells with the specic COX-1 inhibitor (FR122047)
did not affect PGI
2
secretion suggesting Brucella stimulation induced
macrophages to produce PGI
2
via COX-2.
To further examine roles of other key players in COX pathway to
prostaglandin induction, an elevation in PGI
2
production was observed
in IL-10-decient macrophage against Brucella infection suggesting that
induction of the host-derived metabolite is negatively regulated by IL-10
which has been proven to be a key regulator of COX pathway (Berg et al.,
2001; Niiro et al., 1995). COX-2 may be directly or indirectly regulated
by anti-inammatory IL-10 at both transcriptional and
post-transcriptional level. The promoter region of COX-2 possesses
NF-kB motifs that have been associated with expression of COX-2
(D’Acquisto et al., 1998). Moreover, several cytokines such as TNF-
α
and IL-1
α
which have been known to induce COX-2 mRNA are sup-
pressed by IL-10 due to downregulation of NF-κB (Berg et al., 2001).
Thus, when endogenous IL-10 was depleted it was likely to result in
increased activation of NF-κB leading to elevated PGI
2
production.
Differ from PGE
2
that may activate its four receptors (EP1-EP4)
depending on type of stimulation, PGI
2
activates IP – a seven trans-
membrane G-protein coupled receptor leading to elevation in cAMP
which subsequently initiates a respective signaling required for several
inhibitory functions such as relaxation of smooth muscle or inhibition of
group 2 innate lymphoid cell responses (El-Haroun et al., 2008; Zhou
et al., 2016). Iloprost (a PGI
2
analogue) reduced the activation of
ERK1/2 and p38 in MAPK signaling to regulate TNF-
α
production in
LPS-stimulated RAW 264.7 (Lo et al., 1998). PGI
2
has been suggested to
regulate bacterial phagocytosis and killing but the mechanism behind
was not clear (Aronoff et al., 2007). In attempt to examine the effect of
PGI
2
on B. abortus infection in RAW 264.7 macrophages, PGI
2
and its
prominent analogue (NS-304) were used. As a result, only Brucella up-
take was inhibited by PGI
2
and NS-304 but not intracellular growth
during early and late infection in macrophages potentially suggesting
the involvement of PGI
2
signaling in Brucella internalization. We found
that adding PGI
2
decreased p38 activity but not ERK1/2 revealing the
inhibition of bacterial uptake is likely through p38 MAPK pathway.
F-actin polymerization has been well known as a crucial mechanism for
phagocytic uptake of pathogens in professional phagocytes (May and
Machesky, 2001). Bacterial phagocytosis and actin polymerization are
modulated by morphine administration in both in vitro and in vivo by a
chain of signal transduction in which elevated intracellular cAMP level
leads to activation of PKA that subsequently inhibits Rac1-GTPase and
p38 MAPK activity (Ninkovic and Roy, 2012). Consistent with the
crosstalk between PKA and MAPK, we found that in IP-decient cells,
treating with PGI
2
did not suppress Brucella internalization suggesting
the binding of PGI
2
to IP induced signal transduction of IP, followed by
modulation of phagocytosis which may be of potential interest. Further
investigation, however, is required to elucidate the observed
phenomenon.
Cytokines are important effectors secreted upon exogenous or
endogenous stimulation. These molecules are a double-edged sword in
bacterial infection. On one side, they play a key role in recruiting im-
mune cells and initiate immune responses required for bacterial clear-
ance. On the other side, they are taken advantage by microbial
pathogens to proliferate and aggravate symptoms. Due to the inhibitory
effect of PGI
2
, we found that cytokine levels were drastically attenuated
in serum from experimented animals . PGI
2
analogue treatment atten-
uated pro-inammatory cytokines including TNF-
α
and IL-6 while an
elevation in anti-inammatory IL-10 in LPS-stimulated BMMs and bone
marrow-derived dendritic cells was observed (Toki et al., 2018). Beside
TNF-
α
and IL-6, quantitated level of IFN-γ in this study was also strongly
dampened, which has been well known to play crucial roles in con-
trolling proliferation of B. abortus and many other intracellular patho-
gens (Murphy et al., 2001). Similarly, the chemokine MCP-1 level in the
Fig. 6. Biosynthesis of PGI
2
and illustration of PGI

present study was highly suppressed in Brucella-challenged mice.
Involvement of TNF-
α
in intracellular growth of Brucella in macrophages
is suggested to be via Omp25 regulation (Luo et al., 2017). In allergic
lung inammation model, administration with PGI
2
analogue triggered
CD4
+
T cells to express more IL-10 which is well-known in promoting
Brucella persistence and suppressing lysosome-mediated killing (Hop
et al., 2018; Xavier et al., 2013). In contrast, IL-6 has been known to
enhance bacterial clearance by controlling bactericidal activity of
macrophages and development of CD8
+
T cells (Hop et al., 2019) while
Brucella infection was exacerbated in IL-12-decient mice (Zhan and
Cheers, 1995). The effect of MCP-1 in Brucella-infected broblast-like
synoviocytes was associated with recruiting inammatory cells to the
site of infection (Scian et al., 2011). Overall, the decreased serum level
of detected cytokines in selexipag-treated mice might not account for the
substantial reduction in bacterial load. Besides, another function of PGI
2
is inhibiting aggregation of platelets which promotes Brucella invasion
into monocytes by forming complexes (Trotta et al., 2018). Therefore,
the capacity of selexipag in restricting bacterial uptake, and/or
impeding platelets aggregating, and/or an unknown bacterial clearance
mechanism driven by selexipag should be responsible for reduced bac-
terial burden in vivo.
Taken together, our study characterized the synthesis of PGI
2
and its
effect in evasion strategy of macrophages against B. abortus, we pro-
posed that suppressive effect of PGI
2
in B. abortus phagocytosis is IP
signaling-dependent (Fig. 6). Our ndings encourage further investiga-
tion on the role of other PGs and the effect of lipoxygenase (LOX)-
derived metabolites (since LOX is COX counterpart in metabolizing AA)
in macrophages as well as other cell types against microbial infection.
